  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- The USA PATRIOT Act\n- The Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Criminalize concealing the source of illegally obtained money\n- Impose reporting requirements for cash transactions over $10,000\n- Establish penalties including fines and imprisonment\n\n3. Primary Enforcement Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation\n\n4. State Level:\nMany states also have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n\n5. International Coordination:\nThe U.S. works with international organizations like FATF (Financial Action Task Force) to combat global money laundering\n\nThese statutes provide comprehensive legal frameworks to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities across various financial sectors.",
